<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-428-155  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 428 155.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Sept 1990 v27 n9 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hotel phone system tracks guest calls. (Sheraton Hotel, DenverTech Center)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Sheraton Hotel in the Denver (CO) Tech Center has installed aWelComm telephone system featuring a Hitachi HCX5000 PBX.andP;  Thesystem was purchased to replace a previous PBX and a standalonecall accounting system that had produced consistently inaccuratebilling and resulted in lost income that could have been as muchas $300 per day.andP;  Neither the PBX manufacturer nor the callaccounting manufacturer would take responsibility for the garbledcommunication between the two systems that created theinaccuracies.andP;  The new system is ISDN-compatible and is tailoredto the lodging industry, offering a range of features includingintegrated call accounting, automatic call distribution, and aProperty Management System interface.andP;  The system handles 64central office trunks, 48 digital lines, and 780 analog lines.andP;  Inaddition to voice communications, the Sheraton uses the system fordata communications in handling reservations and to generatemonthly reports.andP;  Administrative offices use either SelecSet 400phones, with high-end digital terminals, or SelecSet 200 phones,digital multi-line phones.andP;  The Automatic Call Distributor is usedextensively in the reservations operations, distributing incomingcalls evenly to reservations agents, ensuring the fastest possibleresponse time.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sheraton Corp. (communication systems).andO;Topic:     Hotel and Motel IndustryPBXAutomatic Call Distributors.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>